Prior to the new Islamic laws, Bruneian women had to provide evidence or witnesses to support allegations of either adultery or cruelty before a divorce could be granted by the Shari’a courts. Now, women have to prove that their husband has committed one of three “crimes”—denial of conjugal rights, physical abuse or adultery.

Although the new laws mark the penalization of spousal abuse, turning one’s back on the person one chose to marry is certainly no way to deal with one’s domestic issues. With legislation that protects violators on the basis of “affection,” it is unclear what remedial action a victim can pursue when the demonstrable evidence she has provided is countered with her husband’s word. If a criminal court will not accept the victim’s version of events as to what happened in her marriage, she is left at the mercy of her husband. The crux of the issue is that faith women place in the sanctity of marriage, that their husband will protect them and that “Allah will always look after them.”
